* Motivation
** Motivation for Federated Learning
- The proliferation of machine learning has caused the appetite for
  data to grow unbounded.
- Companies will gladly offer free services in exchange for data. The
  lackadaisical "I don't have anything to hide" approach to privacy has
  made this easier too. But preserving privacy will be one the
  paramount task in the coming years.
- How do we utilize the power of machine learning without sacrificing
  user's privacy? Federated Learning attempts to solve this problem by
  only sharing the weights or model updates while never moving the
  data.
** Motivation for FL in Medical Image analysis
- Just like any other ML algorithm FL gets better with more data. But
  there are strict laws and regulations about sharing medical
  data. Conventional centralized learning cannot be applied to the
  healthcare sector. FL can solve both of these problems.  It enables
  learning from a large pool of data while simultaneously not
  requiring any data sharing.

- It is almost impossible to do any ML work on medical data alone. The
  small dataset problem haunts this field as it does everything else.
  We cannot learn any generalizable facts from a small dataset in any
  field let alone a domain with so much variance as medicine.

 - Even if we are able to procure large amounts of data in a single
   hospital or a lab they would be ridden with local biases such as
   climate, food, culture, socio-economic conditions etc... So we are
   stuck in paradoxical situation where any meaningful work demands
   pooling of data from heterogeneous sources while simultaneously(and
   thankfully) laws prevent any information sharing of patient data.
   FL has allowed to solve this situation.

* Typical steps

Federated learning can be thought of having two nested loops where the
first loop runs on the server and the nested loop runs parallelly on
all the clients
#+BEGIN_SRC python
  model = Model()

  while(global_metric < threshold):
      clients = select_clients()

      for c in clients:
  	send_current_model(model)

      for c in clients:
  	updates = receive_updates()

      model.update(aggregate(updates))

  deploy(model)
#+END_SRC

#+BEGIN_SRC python
  model = receive_model()
  delta_list = []
